# binary : `addrd` — the DNS server daemon that powers addr.tools, a set
#          of DNS-based debugging and reachability tools (whoami.addr.
#          tools, ports.addr.tools, etc.)
#
# Source-direct completion: every flag below is verbatim from cmd/addrd/
# addrd.go on the brianshea2/addr.tools tip — Go stdlib `flag.StringVar`
# / `flag.UintVar` registrations parsed exactly as declared.
#
# Direct deps (selected) from go.mod + cmd/addrd/addrd.go imports:
#   github.com/miekg/dns      ← canonical Go pure-Go DNS library (this
#                                axis) — by Miek Gieben (miekg);
#                                idiomatic Go DNS protocol encoder/
#                                decoder + client + server framework
#                                with full RR-type coverage (every RR
#                                from RFC 1035 onwards including TSIG,
#                                DNSSEC, EDNS0 options, SVCB/HTTPS, etc.)
#                                + zone-file parsing.  THE canonical Go
#                                DNS library — used by CoreDNS, doggo,
#                                go-acme/lego, gobuster, DNSCrypt-proxy,
#                                NextDNS CLI, blocky, dnsproxy,
#                                cloudflare-ddns, ddns-updater, every
#                                Let's Encrypt ACME DNS-01 implementation
#                                in Go, and addrd (this CLI).
#   github.com/brianshea2/addr.tools/internal/{config,dnsutil}
#                              (internal config parser + DNSSEC helpers
#                               that drive the dnsutil.GenerateDnssec-
#                               Provider call path)
#
# addrd is the authoritative DNS server backing the addr.tools website
# (a collection of DNS-based introspection tools).  Two modes:
#   1. Serve DNS — `addrd -c config.toml` runs the daemon with config
#      file defining zones, response handlers (`whoami` echo-back of
#      query source IP, port-reachability checks, etc.), and TSIG
#      keys.  Optionally bind-mounts a TUF root for trusted-zone
#      anchoring.
#   2. DNSSEC keygen — `addrd -k example.com` generates DNSSEC keys
#      for a zone (algorithm selectable via `-a`; defaults to ECDSAP256-
#      SHA256 = algorithm 13).  Prints DS record + signing key + base64-
#      encoded private key on a single line for piping into ops tooling.
#
# === AXIS 178 CONTINUES — pure-language DNS libraries (resolver+protocol) =
# Axis position: Go=233 continues Axis 178 (slot 2/0/0).  Canonical Go
# pure-language DNS library is `github.com/miekg/dns` by Miek Gieben
# (miekg) — idiomatic Go DNS protocol encoder/decoder + client + server
# framework with full RR-type coverage from RFC 1035 onwards (TSIG,
# DNSSEC, EDNS0, SVCB/HTTPS, every modern RR type) + zone-file parsing.
# THE canonical Go DNS library — every notable Go DNS tool in the
# ecosystem depends on it: CoreDNS (which Miek co-created), doggo, go-
# acme/lego, gobuster, DNSCrypt-proxy, NextDNS CLI, blocky, dnsproxy,
# cloudflare-ddns, ddns-updater, every Let's Encrypt ACME DNS-01
# implementation in Go, projectdiscovery's dnsx/interactsh, and addrd.
#
# Cycle position in current 3+1 micro-cycle:
#   Rust=233     _ttl                  ← previous round (axis 178 OPENS, 1/0/0)
#   Go=233       ← THIS FILE           (axis 178 continues, slot 2/0/0)
#   TS-Node=233  ← next round          (axis 178 CLOSES at triple-233, 1/1/1)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

_addrd() {
    _arguments -s \
        '(- *)-h[print help (Go stdlib flag default)]' \
        '-c=[configuration file (TOML format; defines zones/handlers/TSIG keys)]:config file:_files -g "*.(toml|TOML|conf)"' \
        '-k=[generate DNSSEC keys for the specified zone and exit (mutually exclusive with -c)]:zone:' \
        '-a=[algorithm to use when generating DNSSEC keys (default 13 = ECDSAP256SHA256)]:algorithm:((5\:RSASHA1 7\:RSASHA1NSEC3SHA1 8\:RSASHA256 10\:RSASHA512 13\:ECDSAP256SHA256 14\:ECDSAP384SHA384 15\:ED25519 16\:ED448))'
}

_addrd "$@"
